title: Schmitz leads Dull in Mid-Am finals
text:
Previous Next 
VERO BEACH — Sammy Schmitz, a three-time Minnesota Player of the Year, leads Streamsong caddie Marc Dull 2-up after 18 holes in Thursday’s finals of the 35th U.S. Mid-Amateur Championship at John’s Island West. 
Schmitz lost the first two holes, but won three of the next four to take the lead in the topsy-turvy match. 
Schmitz, 35, won three more holes on the back nine — Dull also won two holes — to take the edge into the lunchtime break. 
“I started off kind of choppy,” said Schmitz, who bogeyed the first two holes. “I got it back to even. Long way to go.” 
Dull, who is trying to become the first caddie to qualify for the Masters since 2000 Mid-Am champ Greg Puga, sank a 10-foot birdie to halve the 17th hole. He also made a key par save on the 18th hole, nearly chipping in from a difficult lie in front of the green. 
“I didn’t play well this morning at all,” Dull said. “He gave me the first couple of holes. I hit some loose shots and didn’t take advantage of any opportunities. 
“I missed a couple of short putts inside 4 feet. The match should be tied. We’re still within striking distance, so it’s there to be had.” 
Schmidt, who used to play recreational hockey left-handed, says the key for him is to concentrate on his score. 
“I want to shoot under par,” he said. “Just get a good start; that’s my focus.” 
The final 18 holes start at 12:30. 
The winner receives an invitation to the Masters, a 10-year exemption into the Mid-Am, a two-year exemption into the U.S. Amateur and is exempt from local U.S. Open qualifying for the next three U.S. Opens. 
The runner-up gets a three-year exemption into the Mid-Am, a spot in next year’s U.S. Amateur and is exempt from local qualifying for next year’s U.S. Open. Copyright 2015 Journal Media Group. All rights reserved. This material may not be published, broadcast, rewritten, or redistributed.
